We children had a pleasing dread of that nimble, sharp, exact man, who madeus explain and name every· thing. Of Scotch stories he had as many original ones as would make a second volume for Dean , Ramsay. How well I remember the very corner of the room in Biggar manse, forty years ago, when from him I got the first shock and relish of humour 3 became conscious of mental tickling3 of a word being made to carry double, and being all the lighter of it. Itis an old story now, but it was new then: a big, perspiring countryman rushed into the Black Bull coach-office, and holding the door, shouted, “ Are yir insides a’ oot ?'' This was my first tast- ing of the flavour of a joke. , Had Dr. Heugh, instead of being the admirable clergyman he was, devoted himself to public civil life, and gone into Parliament, he would have taken a high place as a debater‚ a practical statesman and patriot.
